  "doc_id": "36573",
  "text": "Mitochondrial dysfunction: The complex association between mitochondrial dysfunction and target organ damage in sepsis has been extensively reviewed. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] The roles of mitochondria reach far beyond energy production and involve diverse metabolic pathways, including cell death. [CITATION_4] Sepsis is associated with mitochondrial dysfunction, which can have remarkable consequences for cells and the health of the host. In brief, early sepsis is associated with a decrease in mitochondrial ATP generation, which is likely mediated by cytokines, reactive oxygen species (ROS), and nitric oxide (NO), [CITATION_5] suggesting an energy deficit that could be related to tissue and organ damage. The mitochondria might trigger cellular apoptosis later in the course of the disease by releasing cytochrome c, for example. [CITATION_6] Although necrosis and apoptosis are present in sepsis, several concerns regarding tissue damage have been raised. In most situations, organ function improves as sepsis is treated, indicating a lack of massive or irreversible anatomic tissue damage. Additionally, one study suggested that apoptosis is a minor feature in the autopsies of septic patients. [CITATION_7] The mitochondria might be associated with an adaptive suspended animation-like state [CITATION_8] in which cells either recover or undergo programmed cell death, depending on the magnitude of the offending event.",
